    bridge:
      "Where the previous chapter ended with Augustus claiming the title 'Son of God' and God-fearers hovering on the margins of synagogues, this chapter opens in a province where Augustus' gospel had been literally carved in stone.",
    body: "Five years after the death of Augustus, the dignitaries of the Koinon Galaton -- the 'Galatian Commonwealth' -- met to honour him as their Saviour and Lord. Once a people defined by 'their talent for inspiring terror,' tall, red-haired, and prone to fighting in the nude, the Galatians had been subdued by Rome and remade in its image. The Via Sebaste, a mighty gash of stone and compacted gravel stretching four hundred miles, served as both guarantor and symbol of Roman might -- for Sebastos, in Greek, meant 'Augustus.' Across the province, his own account of his career was reproduced on temple walls and triple-arched gateways. His birth, so inscriptions proclaimed, had set the order of things on a new course. Here was Euangelion -- 'Good News.' Never before had the renown of a god spread so fast, so far.",
