    body: "In 1095, Gregory's successor Urban II stood before a vast crowd at Clermont and issued a call that would echo through the centuries. The holy places in Jerusalem, he declared, had been defiled by Muslim rule. Christians must take up arms and liberate them. 'God wills it!' the crowd roared. Holland notes that 'the idea of a holy war, fought under papal authority and blessed with the promise of salvation, was something altogether new.' Tens of thousands answered the call. Knights sewed crosses onto their tunics — they were crucesignati, 'those signed with the cross.' When they stormed Jerusalem in 1099, the slaughter was appalling: 'blood ran ankle-deep through the streets.' Yet the crusaders wept with joy as they knelt at the Holy Sepulchre. The Crusade fused pilgrimage with warfare, penance with conquest. It was 'the most startling demonstration imaginable of the power of the reformed papacy to reshape the world.'",
