    body: "In the wake of Gregory's reforms, the Church developed a comprehensive legal system that Holland describes as 'a framework of law that had no parallel anywhere in the world.' Canon lawyers in Bologna compiled, codified, and systematised centuries of papal decretals, conciliar canons, and patristic writings into a coherent body of jurisprudence. Gratian's Decretum, completed around 1140, 'served the Church much as the Digest had served Justinian's empire.' It regulated everything from marriage and inheritance to contracts and oaths. The reach of ecclesiastical courts extended into every parish. Holland observes that 'the Christian people, from the greatest to the least, were being set within a framework of law as all-embracing as anything decreed by a Roman emperor.' This was not merely reform but the construction of a new kind of sovereignty — one grounded not in the sword but in the authority to interpret God's will.",
