    body: "The same reforming spirit that animated Gregory's papacy drove thousands into the cloister. New monastic orders proliferated. The Cistercians, founded in 1098, sought to recover the original purity of Benedict's Rule by retreating into the wilderness, clearing forests, and living by manual labour. Their most famous son, Bernard of Clairvaux, became 'the most powerful churchman in Christendom who was not a pope.' He thundered against luxury, rebuked kings, and preached the Second Crusade. Holland writes that Bernard 'embodied the conviction that holiness was not a quality to be hoarded but a force to be unleashed upon the world.' The Cistercian ideal — austerity, self-sufficiency, and distance from corruption — spread across Europe with astonishing speed. By the mid-twelfth century, hundreds of Cistercian houses dotted the landscape 'from Scotland to the frontiers of Poland.'",
