    body: "God, expelling Eve from Eden, had sentenced her not just to suffer childbirth but 'to be ruled over by her husband.' Church Fathers had upheld this judgement: 'Do you not know that you are each an Eve?' Augustine, by embedding the doctrine of original sin, 'had bequeathed a sombre sense of the muscle and blood of every womb as infected by the ineradicable taint of disobedience to God.' The great convulsion of reformatio, by enshrining celibacy as proof of closeness to God, 'had only confirmed priests in their dread of women as temptresses.' One Dominican thundered that woman was 'the confusion of man, an insatiable beast, a continuous anxiety, an incessant warfare, a daily ruin, a house of tempest, a hindrance to devotion.' Friars who walked streets crowded with women, 'observing their hair, their breasts, their hips, had to be even more sternly on their guard.' Aristotle provided further ammunition: 'The female is, as it were, an inadequate male.'",
