  bridge:
    "Holland opens with a radical experiment in Christian communism on the hills of Surrey.",
  body: "On 1 April 1649, obedient to what he believed was a direct command of the Holy Spirit, a bankrupt cloth-merchant named Gerrard Winstanley took his spade to St George's Hill and broke the ground. The entire earth, he declared, was 'a common Treasury for all, both Rich and Poor.' Various men and women joined him, and despite hostility from neighbouring landowners, the 'Diggers' kept busy among their corn, carrots and beans. Winstanley proclaimed that monarchy was a usurpation of the power of God, and so too was the rule of every lord. He took literally the warnings of scripture, which 'threaten misery to rich men, bidding them Howl and weep.' The return of Christ, which he believed imminent, would not be from the heavens but in the flesh of ordinary men and women. To dig on St George's Hill was to regain paradise.",
