    "Holland opens with a murder mystery that would ignite Europe's most famous campaign against religious fanaticism.",
  body: "On 13 October 1762, the evening calm of the rue des Filatiers was disturbed by a terrible howl of anguish. In the shop of Jean Calas, a cloth-merchant in his sixties, his eldest son Marc-Antoine was found dead with the unmistakable imprint of a rope on his neck. Calas changed his story — first claiming murder, then confessing he had cut down a hanging corpse. The investigating magistrate had a different hypothesis: Calas, a Huguenot in a country where it was illegal to be anything other than Catholic, had killed his son to prevent his conversion. Marc-Antoine was commemorated in Toulouse's cathedral as a martyr for the Catholic faith. The old man was waterboarded, then lashed to a wheel in the place St-Georges, his limbs broken with an iron bar. 'I die innocent,' he declared. 'Jesus Christ, who was innocence itself, died for me by even more cruel torments.'",
