  bridge:
    "News of the judicial murder reached Europe's most dangerous pen — and gave it a cause.",
  body: "Voltaire, France's greatest writer, the confidant and adversary of kings, immediately became obsessed by the case. Inclined at first to believe in Calas' guilt, he soon changed his mind after interviewing one of Calas' refugee sons in Geneva — 'a simple child, ingenuous, with the most gentle and interesting cast of features.' Calas seemed to Voltaire as much a victim of murderous fanaticism as the Albigensians had once been. Voltaire had long veiled his hatred for Christianity, but now, with properties strategically placed beyond the reach of both French and Genevan authorities, he grew more forthright. The deftness with which he mocked Christians for their god who could be eaten in a morsel of pastry, their scriptures rife with contradictions and idiocies, was unmistakable. When he publicly called for l'infame — 'the abomination' — to be smashed, he did not need to specify his target. Its bigotry had served 'to cover the earth with corpses.'",
