  heading: "THE NEW PHILOSOPHY",
  bridge:
    "Voltaire was not alone — a whole constellation of philosophes shared his contempt for Christianity.",
  body: "Denis Diderot, an atheist and notorious freethinker, hailed Voltaire as 'Antichrist' in a letter of admiration. Ranged alongside them were metaphysicians and encyclopaedists, historians and geologists, whose scorn for l'infame was no less than Voltaire's. Whether in Edinburgh or Naples, in Philadelphia or Berlin, the men most celebrated for their genius increasingly equated churches with bigotry. To be a philosophe was to thrill to the possibility that a new age of freedom was advancing. The demons of superstition were being cast out. Yet Voltaire himself, in his more sombre moments, worried that the malign hold of priestcraft might never be loosened. His age was a siecle des lumieres: 'an age of enlightenment.' For the first time since Constantine, the commanding heights of European culture had been wrested from Christian intellectuals. 'It seems, then, that fanaticism, outraged by the progress of reason, is thrashing about in a spasm of outrage.'",
