  bridge:
    "Holland opens with a scene of staggering courage and horror on the banks of an Indian river.",
  body: "Late in the afternoon of 29 November 1825, a British surgeon arrived on the banks of the Vishwamitri river to watch a young woman be burnt alive. Richard Hartley Kennedy knew he had no authority to stop what was about to happen. Ambabai, her hair dishevelled and her expression severe, circled the pyre with her eyes fixed on her dead husband's body. She was handed a mirror and declared that she had seen the history of her soul, which would soon be returning 'into the bosom and substance of the Creator.' Climbing onto the pyre, she made herself comfortable beside his corpse and began to sing her own funeral song. Even as the pyre was lit, she continued to chant. She never changed her position. Nor did she ever scream. By midnight, nothing was left save a heap of grey and powdery ashes. Ambabai had become what she had set out to become: a 'good woman,' a sati.",
