  heading: "PAGANISM MEETS AWE",
  bridge:
    "The British saw idolatry — but also something they could not easily dismiss.",
  body: "Reports of 'suttee' filled the pages of London newspapers, combining titillation with evidence of Christianity's invincible superiority to paganism. Behind Kennedy's report was a horror of idolatry reaching back through Christian history — Cortes confronting racks of skulls, Boniface venturing into Saxon forests, Origen scorning blood-caked altars. The conviction that idols were raised to demons, witness to 'the extent and power of Satan's empire,' exerted a firm grip on British evangelicals. Yet Kennedy also saluted 'the heavenly aspirations and glowing enthusiasm of her mind.' The sheer antiquity of Indian civilisation inspired awe: Hindus had scriptures as old as the Bible, temples rivalling the cathedrals of Europe, an entire social class — 'Brahmins' — who appeared much like priests. Indeed, one British officer declared, there was little need of Christianity 'to render its votaries a sufficiently correct and moral people.'",
