  body: "Dutch Calvinists who settled the Cape had 'viewed themselves not as colonists, but as a chosen people brought into a promised land.' By 1948, a policy of apartheid had been formalised. 'White rule was enshrined as the expression of God's purpose.' It was maintained not by guns alone but by theology. Yet Desmond Tutu, the first black Archbishop of Cape Town, condemned it as 'totally un-Christian, evil and a heresy.' When clergy demonstrated from Calvin's own writings that apartheid had no biblical support, 'a hammer-blow was dealt to the apartheid regime as decisive as anything delivered by armed insurgents.' If it was as a theological construct that apartheid had been built, then as a theological construct it would need to be dismantled.",
