  heading: "BUSH'S CRUSADE",
  bridge:
    "When America went to war in the name of universal values, it could not see how Christian those values were.",
  body: "After 9/11, George W. Bush asked: 'Why do they hate us?' He answered that terrorists hated America's freedoms — freedoms he believed were universal. Asked to name his favourite thinker, he answered unhesitatingly: 'Christ, because he changed my heart.' Bush insisted: 'We respect the faith. We honor its traditions. Our enemy does not.' He saw no clash of civilisations, for American values were as much the patrimony of Muslims as of Christians. Yet in Iraq, 'sweets and flowers were notable by their absence.' Fanon's insistence that 'it is naked violence, and only gives in when confronted with greater violence' proved more prophetic. Even Fanon, though, had framed his revolution in Jesus' words: decolonisation 'can be summed up in the well-known words: The last shall be first.'",
