  body: "At the Women's March convention in Detroit, the panel 'Confronting White Womanhood' offered white feminists 'the chance to acknowledge their own entitlement, to confess their sins and to be granted absolution.' Holland traces a lineage: 'It had inspired Paulinus to give away his wealth, and Francis to strip himself naked before the Bishop of Assisi, and Elizabeth of Hungary to toil in a hospital as a scullery maid.' A dread of damnation, a yearning for election, a desperation to be cleansed of original sin 'had provided, from the very moment the Pilgrim Fathers set sail, the surest and most fertile seedbed for the ideals of the American people.' The conveners' ambition, like that of preachers before them, 'was to serve as a city on a hill.'",
