  bridge:
    "Holland turns to his own story — a childhood obsession with prehistoric monsters that slowly extinguished his faith.",
  body: "Holland's godmother gave him his first children's Bible, took him fossil-hunting on the Dorset coast, and modelled what Christian faith could mean in daily life. Yet gazing at ichthyosaurs, his belief in God faded. 'The reaches of time seemed too icily immense for the life and death of a single human being two thousand years ago possibly to have had the cosmic significance claimed for it by Christianity.' When his godmother lay dying, she assured him 'that all would be well, and all would be well, and all manner of thing would be well.' He did not share her faith. 'There is nothing particular about man. He is but a part of this world' — yet Holland notes it was Himmler who said this, and the Nazis who 'claimed it as their sanction for genocide.' The implications of denying human specialness remain unsettling.",
