  body: "Standing amid the ruins of Sinjar, on the frontier with the Islamic State, Holland saw crucifixions and enslavement — 'the stench of heat and corpses as the marker of a conqueror's possession.' This was the way of the world: 'Terror of power was the index of power.' Yet for two thousand years, Christians had disputed this. Their own had often become agents of terror, 'but the standards by which they stand condemned for this are themselves Christian.' Holland's final reflection is unsparing: 'If secular humanism derives not from reason or from science, but from the distinctive course of Christianity's evolution — a course that has left God dead — then how are its values anything more than the shadow of a corpse?' Yet a myth is not a lie. 'God chose the weak things of the world to shame the strong. This is the myth that we in the West still persist in clinging to. Christendom, in that sense, remains Christendom still.'",
